# fixleases.template — Static DHCP lease template
# Deploy as: /var/ipfire/dhcp/fixleases on IPFire (rename from .template)
#
# FORMAT: MAC,IP,hostname,enabled,nextIP,remark,interface
# Field 0: MAC address (lowercase, colon-separated)
# Field 1: IP address (MUST be outside dynamic range 192.168.1.100-200)
# Field 2: Hostname (becomes DNS entry automatically — no spaces)
# Field 3: enabled (use "on" to enable, blank to disable)
# Field 4: nextIP (leave blank)
# Field 5: remark (leave blank or short description — no commas)
# Field 6: interface (leave blank for GREEN default)
#
# IP RANGE DESIGN:
#   Static assignments: 192.168.1.2  - 192.168.1.99   (reserve for known hosts)
#   Dynamic pool:       192.168.1.100 - 192.168.1.200 (set in DHCP WUI)
#   IPFire GREEN IP:    192.168.1.1   (gateway — never assign to a client)
#
# CRITICAL: After deploying this file, open WUI > Network > DHCP Server.
# Each entry must be toggled off then on once so WUI writes the host block
# to dhcpd.conf. Without this step, clients will NOT receive static IPs.
#
# DEPLOY STEPS:
#   1. Edit this file with real MACs and IPs (remove comment lines)
#   2. scp configs/dhcp/fixleases root@192.168.1.1:/var/ipfire/dhcp/fixleases
#   3. ssh root@192.168.1.1 'sed -i "s/\r$//" /var/ipfire/dhcp/fixleases'
#   4. Open WUI > Network > DHCP Server — verify entries appear
#   5. Toggle each entry off then on to force dhcpd.conf host block generation
#   6. ssh root@192.168.1.1 '/etc/init.d/dhcp restart'
#   7. Verify: grep "hardware ethernet" /var/ipfire/dhcp/dhcpd.conf
#
# EXAMPLE ENTRIES (replace with real MACs and IPs):
# aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:01,192.168.1.10,server01,on,,,
# aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:02,192.168.1.11,nas01,on,,,
# aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:03,192.168.1.12,workstation01,on,,,
